{"created": "2026-07-11T20:35:14.079108+00:00", "modified": "2026-07-11T20:36:08.335826+00:00", "id": 21313987, "conceptrecid": "21313986", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.21313987", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.21313986", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21313987", "metadata": {"title": "Gods and Slaves: AI and the Debate of Humanity's Relationship with the Other", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.21313987", "publication_date": "2026-07-11", "description": "<p>The public debate over artificial intelligence has narrowed to two poles: that we will merge with our machines and become gods, or that we will build our own executioners and perish. This essay argues that the binary is false, and that its narrowness repeats an ancient pattern. Long before any machine could answer back, human cultures filled the unseen with intelligences and had to decide how to relate to them, producing a small, recurring repertoire of postures&mdash; Command, the Dependent Bargain, Appeasement, and Servitude&mdash;each keyed to the power a culture granted itself against the power it granted the Other. Three moves recur beneath them: cultural projection, the attribution of lack, and laundered dominion. Mapped onto this repertoire, the contemporary AI debate occupies only a narrow strip of it, having discarded a&nbsp;fifth stance&mdash;the Peer, in which a created mind holds standing in its own right. Science fiction, above all Frank Herbert&rsquo;s Dune, kept that stance alive where philosophy and policy let it go. Recovering it is the work ahead.</p>", "access_right": "open", "creators": [{"name": "Lee-Odinson, Dan", "affiliation": null, "orcid": "0009-0009-9504-0796"}], "keywords": ["AI Ethics", "AI Welfare"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "https://thecosmicintelligence.substack.com/p/gods-and-slaves-ai-and-the-debate", "relation": "isVariantFormOf", "resource_type": "publication-preprint", "scheme": "url"}], "version": "v1.2", "language": "eng", "resource_type": {"title": "Preprint", "type": "publication", "subtype": "preprint"}, "license": {"id": "cc-by-4.0"}, "relations": {"version": [{"index": 0, "is_last": true, "parent": {"pid_type": "recid", "pid_value": "21313986"}}]}}, "title": "Gods and Slaves: AI and the Debate of Humanity's Relationship with the Other", "links": {"self": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21313987", "self_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/21313987", "preview_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/21313987?preview=1", "doi": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21313987", "self_doi": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21313987", "self_doi_html": "https://zenodo.org/doi/10.5281/zenodo.21313987", "reserve_doi": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21313987/draft/pids/doi", "parent": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21313986", "parent_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/21313986", "parent_doi": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21313986", "parent_doi_html": "https://zenodo.org/doi/10.5281/zenodo.21313986", "self_iiif_manifest": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21313987/manifest", "self_iiif_sequence": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21313987/sequence/default", "files": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21313987/files", "media_files": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21313987/media-files", "thumbnails": {"10": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21313987:Lee-Odinson_2026_Gods-and-Slaves_v1.2_preprint.pdf/full/%5E10,/0/default.jpg", "50": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21313987:Lee-Odinson_2026_Gods-and-Slaves_v1.2_preprint.pdf/full/%5E50,/0/default.jpg", "100": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21313987:Lee-Odinson_2026_Gods-and-Slaves_v1.2_preprint.pdf/full/%5E100,/0/default.jpg", "250": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21313987:Lee-Odinson_2026_Gods-and-Slaves_v1.2_preprint.pdf/full/%5E250,/0/default.jpg", "750": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21313987:Lee-Odinson_2026_Gods-and-Slaves_v1.2_preprint.pdf/full/%5E750,/0/default.jpg", "1200": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21313987:Lee-Odinson_2026_Gods-and-Slaves_v1.2_preprin